The New York Shipping Association andInternational Longshoremen's Association said they agreed tocut cargo assessments at the Port of New York and New Jersey bymore than 50 pct on some labor intensive cargos.    The charges on cargo handled by union workers will bereduced to 2.85 dlrs a ton from 5.85 dlrs a ton, effectiveApril one, according to the agreement between the union andshippers. The assessments are used to fund workers' benefits.    "What were doing is lowering the price to get more bulkcargo flowing through here," a spokesman for the New YorkShipping Association said.&#3;